# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: yugabytedb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] YugabyteDB is a distributed database that seamlessly combines the principles of distributed systems, where multiple machines collaborate, with the familiar concepts of traditional databases, where data is organized in tables with standard interfaces for reading and writing data.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] Unlike traditional centralized databases, YugabyteDB is designed to manage and process data across multiple nodes or servers, ensuring resiliency, consistency, high availability, scalability, fault tolerance, and other design goals.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] In general, operations in YugabyteDB are split logically into 2 layers, the query layer and the storage layer.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] The query layer is responsible for handling user requests and sending the requests to the right data.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] The storage layer is responsible for optimally storing the data on disk and managing replication and consistency.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] For operating (CRUD) on the data that is split and stored across multiple machines, YugabyteDB provides two APIs, YSQL and YCQL.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] The query layer takes the user query submitted via the API and sends or fetches data to and from the right set of tablets.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] The tablet data is optimally stored and managed by DocDB, a document store that has been built on top of RocksDB for higher performance and persistence.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] YugabyteDB splits table data into smaller pieces called tablets so that the data can be stored in parts across multiple machines.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] The mapping of a row to a tablet is deterministic and this process is known as sharding.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] Tablets are replicated for resiliency, high availability, and fault tolerance.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] Each tablet has a leader that is responsible for consistent reads and writes to the data of the tablet and a few followers.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] The replication is done using the Raft protocol to ensure consistency of data across the leader and followers.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] Transactions are a set of operations (CRUD) that are executed atomically with the option to roll back all actions if any operation fails.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] The master service acts a catalog manager and cluster orchestrator, and manages many background tasks.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] YugabyteDB splits table data into tablets.
[src:yugabytedb/architecture] These tablets are maintained and managed on each node by the TServer.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] A **distributed SQL** database is a single relational database which replicates data across multiple servers.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Distributed SQL databases are strongly consistent and most support consistency across racks, data centers, and wide area networks including cloud availability zones and cloud geographic zones.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Distributed SQL databases typically use the Paxos or Raft algorithms to achieve consensus across multiple nodes.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Sometimes distributed SQL databases are referred to as NewSQL but NewSQL is a more inclusive term that includes databases that are not distributed databases.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Google's Spanner popularized the modern distributed SQL database concept.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Spanner uses atomic clocks with the Paxos algorithm to accomplish consensus with regards to state distributed between servers.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] In 2010, and earlier implementation, ClustrixDB (now MariaDB Xpand) moved from a hardware appliance to a Paxos-based software database and was later acquired by MariaDB and added to a SaaS cloud offering called SkySQL.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] In 2015, two Google engineers left the company to create Cockroach DB which achieves similar results using the Raft algorithm without atomic clocks or custom hardware.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Spanner is primarily used for transactional and time-series use cases.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] However, Google furthered this research with a follow on paper about Google F1 which it describes as a Hybrid transactional/analytical processing database built on Spanner.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Following the CAP Theorem, distributed SQL databases are "CP" or consistent and partition-tolerant.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Algorithmically they sacrifice availability in that a failure of a primary node can make the database unavailable for writes.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] All distributed SQL implementations require some kind of temporal synchronization to guarantee consistency.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] With the exception of Spanner, most do not use custom hardware to provide atomic clocks.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Spanner is able to synchronize writes with temporal guarantees.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Implementations without custom hardware require servers to compare clock offsets and potentially retry reads.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] CockroachDB, YugabyteDB and others have at times referred to themselves as NewSQL databases.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Some of the NewSQL databases have fundamentally different architectures, but were cited as examples of NewSQL by Matthew Aslett who coined the term.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] In essence, distributed SQL databases are built from the ground-up and NewSQL databases include replication and sharding technologies added to existing client-server relational databases like PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/distributed-sql] Some experts define DistributedSQL databases as a more specific subset of NewSQL databases.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] YugabyteDB is a cloud-native distributed PostgreSQL-compatible database that combines strong consistency with ultra-resilience, seamless scalability, geo-distribution, and highly flexible data locality to deliver business-critical, transactional applications.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] Available as a flexible service and with a uniform experience across Kubernetes and/or any combination of public, private, or hybrid cloud, YugabyteDB provides distributed PostgreSQL that scales and never fails.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] YugabyteDB provides PostgreSQL without limits and is an excellent fit for new or modernized transactional applications that need absolute data correctness and require scalability, high availability, or global deployment.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] Create your first cluster and build a sample application in 15 minutes.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] Streamline all stages of bringing a source to YugabyteDB, including analysis, conversion, migration, and cutover.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] Explore YugabyteDB's support for cloud-native applications.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] Add a scalable and highly-available database to your AI projects.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] Learn about YugabyteDB's modern architecture.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] Use your favorite programming language to build an application that connects to a YugabyteDB cluster.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] Connect applications to your database using familiar third-party divers and ORMs and YugabyteDB Smart Drivers.
[src:yugabytedb/docs-yugabyte-com] Get up to speed quickly using YugabyteDB's PostgreSQL-compatible YSQL and Cassandra-based YCQL APIs.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The PostgreSQL Global Development Group focuses only on developing a database engine and closely related components.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This core is, technically, what comprises PostgreSQL itself, but there is an extensive developer community and ecosystem that provides other important feature sets that might, traditionally, be provided by a proprietary software vendor.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] These include special-purpose database engine features, like those needed to support a geospatial or temporal database or features which emulate other database products.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Also available from third parties are a wide variety of user and machine interface features, such as graphical user interfaces or load balancing and high availability toolsets.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The large third-party PostgreSQL support network of people, companies, products, and projects, even though not part of The PostgreSQL Development Group, are essential to the PostgreSQL database engine's adoption and use and make up the PostgreSQL ecosystem writ large.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL was originally named POSTGRES, referring to its origins as a successor to the Ingres database developed at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] After a review in 2007, the development team decided to keep the name PostgreSQL and the alias Postgres.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL evolved from the Ingres project at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In 1982, the leader of the Ingres team, Michael Stonebraker, left Berkeley to make a proprietary version of Ingres.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] He returned to Berkeley in 1985, and began a post-Ingres project to address the problems with contemporary database systems that had become increasingly clear during the early 1980s.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] He won the Turing Award in 2014 for these and other projects, and techniques pioneered in them.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The new project, POSTGRES, aimed to add the fewest features needed to completely support data types.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] These features included the ability to define types and to fully describe relationships – something used widely, but maintained entirely by the user.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In POSTGRES, the database understood relationships, and could retrieve information in related tables in a natural way using *rules*.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] POSTGRES used many of the ideas of Ingres, but not its code.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Starting in 1986, published papers described the basis of the system, and a prototype version was shown at the 1988 ACM SIGMOD Conference.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The team released version 1 to a small number of users in June 1989, followed by version 2 with a re-written rules system in June 1990.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Version 3, released in 1991, again re-wrote the rules system, and added support for multiple storage managers and an improved query engine.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] By 1993, the number of users began to overwhelm the project with requests for support and features.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] After releasing version 4.2 on June 30, 1994 – primarily a cleanup – the project ended.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Berkeley released POSTGRES under an MIT License variant, which enabled other developers to use the code for any use.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] At the time, POSTGRES used an Ingres-influenced POSTQUEL query language interpreter, which could be interactively used with a console application named monitor.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In 1994, Berkeley graduate students Andrew Yu and Jolly Chen replaced the POSTQUEL query language interpreter with one for the SQL query language, creating Postgres95.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The monitor console was also replaced by psql.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Yu and Chen announced the first version (0.01) to beta testers on May 5, 1995.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Version 1.0 of Postgres95 was announced on September 5, 1995, with a more liberal license that enabled the software to be freely modifiable.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] On July 8, 1996, Marc Fournier at Hub.org Networking Services provided the first non-university development server for the open-source development effort.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] With the participation of Bruce Momjian and Vadim B.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Mikheev, work began to stabilize the code inherited from Berkeley.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed to PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The online presence at the website PostgreSQL.org began on October 22, 1996.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The first PostgreSQL release formed version 6.0 on January 29, 1997.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Since then developers and volunteers around the world have maintained the software as The PostgreSQL Global Development Group.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The project continues to make releases available under its free and open-source software PostgreSQL License.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Code comes from contributions from proprietary vendors, support companies, and open-source programmers.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] As of 2025, PostgreSQL is on major release version 18 which is notable in implementing asynchronous I/O (AIO), enabling database users to perform concurrent I/O tasks like readahead and sequential scan.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages concurrency through multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), which gives each transaction a "snapshot" of the database, allowing changes to be made without affecting other transactions.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This largely eliminates the need for read locks, and ensures the database maintains ACID principles.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL offers four levels of transaction isolation: Read Uncommitted, Read Committed, Repeatable Read and Serializable.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Because PostgreSQL is immune to dirty reads, requesting a Read Uncommitted transaction isolation level provides read committed instead.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports full serializability via the serializable snapshot isolation (SSI) method.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The PostgreSQL MVCC implementation is prone to performance issues that require tuning when under a heavy write load which updates existing rows.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in binary replication based on shipping the changes (write-ahead logs (WAL)) to replica nodes asynchronously, with the ability to run read-only queries against these replicated nodes.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This allows splitting read traffic among multiple nodes efficiently.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Earlier replication software that allowed similar read scaling normally relied on adding replication triggers to the master, increasing load.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in synchronous replication that ensures that, for each write transaction, the master waits until at least one replica node has written the data to its transaction log.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Unlike other database systems, the durability of a transaction (whether it is asynchronous or synchronous) can be specified per-database, per-user, per-session or even per-transaction.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This can be useful for workloads that do not require such guarantees, and may not be wanted for all data as it slows down performance due to the requirement of the confirmation of the transaction reaching the synchronous standby.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Standby servers can be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Synchronous standby servers can be specified in the configuration which determines which servers are candidates for synchronous replication.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The first in the list that is actively streaming will be used as the current synchronous server.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] When this fails, the system fails over to the next in line.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL's replication can trigger conflicts between the primary and standby servers, particularly whenever tuples are prematurely deleted from the standby server despite ongoing queries accessing them.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] To address this, PostgreSQL includes a feedback flag where the standby server proactively informs the primary server of any ongoing queries to mitigate this type of conflict.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Synchronous multi-master replication is not included in the PostgreSQL core.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Postgres-XC which is based on PostgreSQL provides scalable synchronous multi-master replication.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] It is licensed under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] A related project is called Postgres-XL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Bidirectional replication (BDR) is an asynchronous multi-master replication system for PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Tools such as repmgr make managing replication clusters easier.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Several asynchronous trigger-based replication packages are available.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in support for regular B-tree and hash table indexes, and four index access methods: generalized search trees (GiST), generalized inverted indexes (GIN), Space-Partitioned GiST (SP-GiST) and Block Range Indexes (BRIN).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In addition, user-defined index methods can be created, although this is quite an involved process.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL schemas are namespaces, allowing objects of the same kind and name to co-exist in a single database.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] They are not to be confused with a database schema—the abstract, structural, organizational specification which defines how every table's data relates to data within other tables.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] All PostgreSQL database objects, except for a few global objects such as roles and tablespaces, exist within a schema.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] They cannot be nested, schemas cannot contain schemas.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The permission system controls access to schemas and their content.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] By default, newly created databases have only a single schema called *public* but other schemas can be added and the public schema isn't mandatory.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] A `search_path` setting determines the order in which PostgreSQL checks schemas for unqualified objects (those without a prefixed schema).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] By default, it is set to `$user, public` (`$user` refers to the currently connected database user).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This default can be set on a database or role level, but as it is a session parameter, it can be freely changed (even multiple times) during a client session, affecting that session only.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Non-existent schemas, or other schemas not accessible to the logged-in user, that are listed in search_path are silently skipped during object lookup.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] New objects are created in whichever valid schema (one that can be accessed) appears first in the search_path.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In addition, users can create their own data types which can usually be made fully indexable via PostgreSQL's indexing infrastructures – GiST, GIN, SP-GiST.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Examples of these include the geographic information system (GIS) data types from the PostGIS project for PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] There is also a data type called a *domain*, which is the same as any other data type but with optional constraints defined by the creator of that domain.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This means any data entered into a column using the domain will have to conform to whichever constraints were defined as part of the domain.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] A data type that represents a range of data can be used which are called range types.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] These can be discrete ranges (e.g. all integer values 1 to 10) or continuous ranges (e.g., any time between 10:00 am and 11:00 am).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The built-in range types available include ranges of integers, big integers, decimal numbers, time stamps (with and without time zone) and dates.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Custom range types can be created to make new types of ranges available, such as IP address ranges using the inet type as a base, or float ranges using the float data type as a base.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Range types support inclusive and exclusive range boundaries using the [] and () characters respectively.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] (e.g., `[4,9)` represents all integers starting from and including 4 up to but not including 9.) Range types are also compatible with existing operators used to check for overlap, containment, right of etc.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Tables can be set to inherit their characteristics from a *parent* table.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Data in child tables will appear to exist in the parent tables, unless data is selected from the parent table using the ONLY keyword, i.e.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Adding a column in the parent table will cause that column to appear in the child table.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Inheritance can be used to implement table partitioning, using either triggers or rules to direct inserts to the parent table into the proper child tables.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In particular, table constraints are not currently inheritable.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] All check constraints and not-null constraints on a parent table are automatically inherited by its children.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Other types of constraints (unique, primary key, and foreign key constraints) are not inherited.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Inheritance provides a way to map the features of generalization hierarchies depicted in entity–relationship diagrams (ERDs) directly into the PostgreSQL database.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL can link to other systems to retrieve data via foreign data wrappers (FDWs).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] These can take the form of any data source, such as a file system, another relational database management system (RDBMS), or a web service.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This means that regular database queries can use these data sources like regular tables, and even join multiple data-sources together.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports a binary communication protocol that allows applications to connect to the database server.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The protocol is versioned (currently 3.0, as of PostgreSQL 7.4) and has a detailed specification.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The official client implementation of this communication protocol is a C API, libpq.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In addition, the officially supported ECPG tool allows SQL commands to be embedded in C code.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Both are part of the standard PostgreSQL distribution.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Third-party libraries for connecting to PostgreSQL are available for many programming languages, including C++, Java, Julia, Python, Node.js, Go, and Rust.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Procedural languages allow developers to extend the database with custom subroutines (functions), often called *stored procedures*.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] These functions can be used to build database triggers (functions invoked on modification of certain data) and custom data types and aggregate functions.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Procedural languages can also be invoked without defining a function, using a DO command at SQL level.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Languages are divided into two groups: Procedures written in *safe* languages are sandboxed and can be safely created and used by any user.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Procedures written in *unsafe* languages can only be created by superusers, because they allow bypassing a database's security restrictions, but can also access sources external to the database.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Some languages like Perl provide both safe and unsafe versions.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In addition, PostgreSQL allows procedural languages to be loaded into the database through extensions.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Three language extensions are included with PostgreSQL to support Perl, Tcl, and Python.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] For Python, the current Python 3 is used, and the discontinued Python 2 is no longer supported as of PostgreSQL 15.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Both were supported previously, defaulting to Python 2, while old and new versions couldn't be used in the same session.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] External projects provide support for many other languages, including PL/Java, JavaScript (PL/V8), PL/Julia, PL/R, PL/Ruby, and others.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Triggers are events triggered by the action of SQL data manipulation language (DML) statements.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] For example, an INSERT statement might activate a trigger that checks if the values of the statement are valid.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Most triggers are only activated by either INSERT or UPDATE statements.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Triggers are fully supported and can be attached to tables.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Triggers can be per-column and conditional, in that UPDATE triggers can target specific columns of a table, and triggers can be told to execute under a set of conditions as specified in the trigger's WHERE clause.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Triggers can be attached to views by using the INSTEAD OF condition.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Multiple triggers are fired in alphabetical order.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In addition to calling functions written in the native PL/pgSQL, triggers can also invoke functions written in other languages like PL/Python or PL/Perl.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL provides an asynchronous messaging system that is accessed through the NOTIFY, LISTEN and UNLISTEN commands.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] A session can issue a NOTIFY command, along with the user-specified channel and an optional payload, to mark a particular event occurring.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Other sessions are able to detect these events by issuing a LISTEN command, which can listen to a particular channel.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This functionality can be used for a wide variety of purposes, such as letting other sessions know when a table has updated or for separate applications to detect when a particular action has been performed.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Such a system prevents the need for continuous polling by applications to see if anything has yet changed, and reducing unnecessary overhead.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Notifications are fully transactional, in that messages are not sent until the transaction they were sent from is committed.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This eliminates the problem of messages being sent for an action being performed which is then rolled back.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Many connectors for PostgreSQL provide support for this notification system (including libpq, JDBC, Npgsql, psycopg and node.js) so it can be used by external applications.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL can act as an effective, persistent "pub/sub" server or job server by combining LISTEN with FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Rules allow the "query tree" of an incoming query to be rewritten; they are an, automatically invoked, macro language for SQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] "Query Re-Write Rules" are attached to a table/class and "Re-Write" the incoming DML (select, insert, update, and/or delete) into one or more queries that either replace the original DML statement or execute in addition to it.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Query Re-Write occurs after DML statement parsing and before query planning.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The functionality rules provide was, in almost every way, later duplicated with the introduction of newer types of triggers.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The use of triggers is usually preferred over rules as it is easier to reason about trigger behavior and interactions than when equivalent rules are used.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL server is process-based (not threaded), and uses one operating system process per database session.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Multiple sessions are automatically spread across all available CPUs by the operating system.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Many types of queries can also be parallelized across multiple background worker processes, taking advantage of multiple CPUs or cores.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Client applications can use threads and create multiple database connections from each thread.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages its internal security on a per-role basis.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] A role is generally regarded to be a user (a role that can log in), or a group (a role of which other roles are members).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Permissions can be granted or revoked on any object down to the column level, and can allow or prevent the visibility/creation/alteration/deletion of objects at the database, schema, table, and row levels.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL's SECURITY LABEL feature (extension to SQL standards), allows for additional security; with a bundled loadable module that supports label-based mandatory access control (MAC) based on Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) security policy.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The GSSAPI, SSPI, Kerberos, peer, ident and certificate methods can also use a specified "map" file that lists which users matched by that authentication system are allowed to connect as a specific database user.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] These methods are specified in the cluster's host-based authentication configuration file (pg_hba.conf), which determines what connections are allowed.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This allows control over which user can connect to which database, where they can connect from (IP address, IP address range, domain socket), which authentication system will be enforced, and whether the connection must use Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL claims high, but not complete, conformance with the latest SQL standard ("as of the version 17 release in September 2024, PostgreSQL conforms to at least 170 of the 177 mandatory features for SQL:2023 Core conformance", and no other databases fully conformed to it).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] One exception is the handling of unquoted identifiers like table or column names.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In PostgreSQL they are folded, internally, to lower case characters whereas the standard says that unquoted identifiers should be folded to upper case.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Thus, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO` not `foo` according to the standard.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Other shortcomings concern the absence of temporal tables allowing automatic logging of row versions during transactions with the possibility of browsing in time (FOR SYSTEM TIME predicate), although relatively SQL compliant third-party extensions are available.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Many informal performance studies of PostgreSQL have been done.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Performance improvements aimed at improving scalability began heavily with version 8.1.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Simple benchmarks between version 8.0 and version 8.4 showed that the latter was more than ten times faster on read-only workloads and at least 7.5 times faster on both read and write workloads.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The first industry-standard and peer-validated benchmark was completed in June 2007, using the Sun Java System Application Server (proprietary version of GlassFish) 9.0 Platform Edition, UltraSPARC T1-based Sun Fire server and PostgreSQL 8.2.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This result of 778.14 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard compares favourably with the 874 JOPS@Standard with Oracle 10 on an Itanium-based HP-UX system.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In August 2007, Sun submitted an improved benchmark score of 813.73 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] With the system under test at a reduced price, the price/performance improved from $84.98/JOPS to $70.57/JOPS.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The default configuration of PostgreSQL uses only a small amount of dedicated memory for performance-critical purposes such as caching database blocks and sorting.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This limitation is primarily because older operating systems required kernel changes to allow allocating large blocks of shared memory.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL.org provides advice on basic recommended performance practice in a wiki.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In April 2012, Robert Haas of EnterpriseDB demonstrated PostgreSQL 9.2's linear CPU scalability using a server with 64 cores.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Matloob Khushi performed benchmarking between PostgreSQL 9.0 and MySQL 5.6.15 for their ability to process genomic data.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In his performance analysis he found that PostgreSQL extracts overlapping genomic regions eight times faster than MySQL using two datasets of 80,000 each forming random human DNA regions.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Insertion and data uploads in PostgreSQL were also better, although general searching ability of both databases was almost equivalent.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] 64-bit Power ISA), SPARC (also 64-bit), MIPS and PA-RISC.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] It was also known to work on some other platforms (while not been tested on for years, i.e. for latest versions).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] , which can be used to enter SQL queries directly, or execute them from a file.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] In addition, psql provides a number of meta-commands and various shell-like features to facilitate writing scripts and automating a wide variety of tasks; for example tab completion of object names and SQL syntax.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] (GUI) administration tool for PostgreSQL, which is supported on many computer platforms.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The program is available in more than a dozen languages.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The second incarnation (named pgAdmin II) was a complete rewrite, first released on January 16, 2002.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] and then released under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] framework allowing it to run on most common operating systems.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The query tool includes a scripting language called pgScript for supporting admin and development tasks.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] announced that with the shift towards web-based models, work has begun on pgAdmin 4 with the aim to facilitate cloud deployments.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to perform essential PostgreSQL database development tasks from a web-based console.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to work with cloud databases without the need to open firewalls.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] AJAX/JavaScript-driven web interface for PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Allows browsing, maintaining and creating data and database objects via a web browser.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] management for commonly used scripts, among other features.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Installers are available for Windows, Macintosh, and Linux, and a simple cross-platform archive that runs from a script.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Base can be used as a front-end for PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] The pgBadger PostgreSQL log analyzer generates detailed reports from a PostgreSQL log file.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] pgDevOps is a suite of web tools to install & manage multiple PostgreSQL versions, extensions, and community components, develop SQL queries, monitor running databases and find performance problems.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] is a simple web-based administration tool for PostgreSQL and others, written in PHP.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] pgBackRest is a backup and restore tool for PostgreSQL that provides support for full, differential, and incremental backups.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] pgaudit is a PostgreSQL extension that provides detailed session and/or object audit logging via the standard logging facility provided by PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Postgresus is an open source backup tool with GUI for scheduled backups with support of external sources (S3, NAS, FTP, Google Drive, Google Cloud, etc.) and notifications to external services (Slack, Discord, Telegram, SMTP, etc.).
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] A number of companies offer proprietary tools for PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] They often consist of a universal core that is adapted for various specific database products.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] These tools mostly share the administration features with the open source tools but offer improvements in data modeling, importing, exporting or reporting.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] Due to its permissive open-source license and extensible architecture, a broad ecosystem has developed around PostgreSQL.
[src:yugabytedb/postgresql] This includes numerous companies offering dedicated support and hosting, as well as several forks and derivative databases that adapt PostgreSQL for specific workloads.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] Yugabyte was founded by ex-Facebook engineers Kannan Muthukkaruppan, Karthik Ranganathan, and Mikhail Bautin.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] At Facebook, they were part of the team that built and operated Cassandra and HBase for workloads such as Facebook Messenger and Facebook's Operational Data Store.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] The founders came together in February 2016 to build YugabyteDB.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] YugabyteDB was initially available in two editions: community and enterprise.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] In July 2019, Yugabyte open-sourced previously commercial features and launched YugabyteDB as open-source under the Apache 2.0 license.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] YugabyteDB is a distributed SQL database that aims to be strongly transactionally consistent across failure zones (i.e.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] In CAP Theorem terms YugabyteDB is a Consistent/Partition Tolerant (CP) database.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] YugabyteDB has two layers, a storage engine known as DocDB and the Yugabyte Query Layer.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] The storage engine consists of a customized RocksDB combined with sharding and load balancing algorithms for the data.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] In addition, the Raft consensus algorithm controls the replication of data between the nodes.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] There is also a Distributed transaction manager and Multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) to support distributed transactions.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] The engine also exploits a Hybrid Logical Clock that combines coarsely-synchronized physical clocks with Lamport clocks to track causal relationships.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] The DocDB layer is not directly accessible by users.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] Yugabyte has a pluggable query layer that abstracts the query layer from the storage layer below.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] Currently, data written to either API is not accessible via the other API, however YSQL can access YCQL using the PostgreSQL foreign data wrapper feature.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] The security model for accessing the system is inherited from the API, so access controls for YSQL look like PostgreSQL, and YCQL looks like Cassandra access controls.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] In addition to its core functionality of distributing a single database, YugabyteDB has the ability to replicate between database instances.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] The replication can be one-way or bi-directional and is asynchronous.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] One-way replication is used either to create a read-only copy for workload off-loading or in a read-write mode to create an active-passive standby.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] Bi-directional replication is generally used in read-write configurations and is used for active-active configurations, geo-distributed applications, etc.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] Yugabyte also provides YugabyteDB Voyager, tooling to facilitate the migration of Oracle and other similar databases to YugabyteDB.
[src:yugabytedb/yugabytedb] This tool supports the migration of schemas, procedural code and data from the source platform to YugabyteDB.
